@{
    ViewBag.Title = "DataClassification";
    ViewBag.Subtitle = "The sensitivity of managed resources";
}
<h2>@ViewBag.Title.</h2>
<h3>@ViewBag.Subtitle</h3>

The <i>Operations</i> that a Principal (ie, User) is permitted to invoke are controlled by <i>Roles</i>.

But access to a <i>Resource</i> is also controlled by the <i>Resource</i>'s <i>DataClassification</i>, and whether the Principal (via the Role's DataClassification) is permitted to access Resources with that <i>DataClassification</i>.

<h3>API Examples</h3>

The following are some example api calls, using OData terms such as $skip, $top, $inlinecount, $expand:

<ul>
    <li><a target="_apis" href="~/OData/core/dataclassification/">DataClassifications</a></li>
    <li><a target="_apis" href="~/OData/core/dataclassification/?$count=true&$top=0">DataClassifications, total Count thereof...</a></li>
    <li><a target="_apis" href="~/OData/core/dataclassification/?$top=3">DataClassifications, Taking 3...</a></li>
    <li><a target="_apis" href="~/OData/core/dataclassification/?$top=2">DataClassifications, Taking 2...</a></li>
    <li><a target="_apis" href="~/OData/core/dataclassification/?$top=1">DataClassifications, Taking just 1.</a></li>
    <li><a target="_apis" href="~/OData/core/dataclassification/?$orderby=Text">DataClassifications, Ordered by a Field.</a></li>
    <li><a target="_apis" href="~/OData/core/dataclassification/?$skip=2&$top=3">DataClassifications, skipping 2, Taking 3</a></li>
    <li><a target="_apis" href="~/OData/core/dataclassification/?$skip=2&$top=3&$count=true">DataClassifications, skipping 2, Taking 3, with totalCount</a></li>
</ul>


